<TEXT>
the soviets cannot go back to a controlled 
economy and cannot go forward to a successful freemarket economy 
without help from the west soviet academicians said friday at a 
meeting with us experts 
the old system is bankrupt said stanislav shatalin head of 
the economics division of the soviet academy of science it is 
difficult for me to admit that but it is a fact 
the soviets he said still have not decided the degree we will 
work with the west in changing the economy 
without the help of the west we cannot establish a successful 
market system shatalin said 
the comments came at a meeting between 10 soviet academicians and 
a group of us industry education and government leaders the 
2hour session at the national academy of sciences centered on a 
candid report by the soviet experts on their nations efforts to 
radically change their economy 
shatalin a member of the presidents council which advises 
soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev said the soviets have tried to 
shift slowly toward a market economy with measures that included 
elements of both a free market and the old centrally controlled 
economy 
the result he said has been like trying to prop up the 
economy with two rocking chairs 
under the measures shatalin said the economic situation has 
worsened and is getting worse every day 
gorbachev who appealed on television for the soviet public to 
remain calm as prices increased does not approve of the entire 
reform package shatalin said 
the president and the presidents council feel quite 
differently he said there is a very big difference between 
their position and the position of the government 
shatalin said he and other advisers to gorbachev are looking at 
other economic options that could be adopted in the coming months 
and yet he said its widely recognized that the soviet union 
cant return to the old centrally controlled economy which he said 
had collapsed 
even our most reactionary thinkers know it is impossible to 
return to the old system even though many believe that system 
provided a minimum floor to protect the population by providing 
assured employment and income shatalin said 
the majority of the population along with the parliaments and 
the local soviets all agree that there is no longer any 
opportunity except to shift to a market system he said 
there is recognition that we have no other path shatalin 
said 
the soviet government plans to raise the price of bread later 
this year and may organize some form of compensation for people who 
would have to pay a larger percentage of their income for bread 
for lowincome workers shatalin said bread represents a major 
part of their diet and they will not be able to tolerate a steep 
rise in prices without government compensation 
and yet he said the question of compensation has been thought 
through in a very slipshod fashion 
shatalin said that many in the soviet union are confused and 
apprehensive about the effects of a freemarket economy and that the 
expected benefits have not been fully explained 
despite that said academician georgiy arbatov the director of 
the soviet institute for studies of the usa and canada there is an 
entrepreneurial gift among the soviet people 
we fought against entrepreneurs for two generations he said 
but was soon as we stopped they broke out and some are very 
gifted 
among the major economic problems that soviet experts are still 
thinking through according to shatalin are 
how to raise interest rates on savings the government pays 3 
percent on rubles deposited in savings accounts yet inflation is 
about 10 percent were going to have to raise interest rates on 
the order of 12 to 15 percent shatalin said 
how to build a system of selling government bonds to the public 
and how to build a stock market for soviet investors 
how to design laws to permit private ownership of land and other 
property we need to make changes in all types of ownership 
shatalin said otherwise we end up in a closed circle 
how to convert the military equipment complexes into factories 
producing consumer goods 
how to develop a banking system that would provide capital loans 
needed by entrepreneurs in a free market 
</TEXT>
