<TEXT>
after 12 years of pushing the conservative 
cause in the us senate political maverick gordon humphrey is 
going home to new hampshire to run for a 100ayear seat in the 
state senate 
humphreys run for the parttime job is no surprise to those who 
watched the former airline pilot and political novice rise to the 
national forefront of conservatism 
given his political career nothing about it would surprise 
me said republican political consultant thomas rath he puts 
the un in unorthodox 
humphrey 49 calls himself probably the senates most outspoken 
antiabortion voice and at times has criticized presidents reagan 
and bush for not being conservative enough notably on taxes and 
sanctions against china 
he said he is running for state office partly because he thinks 
new hampshire is straying from its conservative roots 
i think the conservative character of the state is being eroded 
and that weve got to try to stop that he said 
he also believes politicians should not make congress a career 
he has said hed like to run for governor at some point but not 
while his friend gov judd gregg holds the office 
humphreys reputation as a conservatives conservative is a far 
cry from his early political experience he was a democratic 
campaign volunteer and local democratic official in virginia in the 
late 1960s and early 1970s which he once called his shameful 
past 
humphrey moved to new hampshire in 1974 and registered 
republican he emerged as state coordinator of the new hampshire 
conservative caucus in 1977 and was elected senator the next year 
the state senate seat opened up because republican william 
johnson is running for congress to succeed bob smith whos 
running for humphreys senate seat 
humphrey who will make his candidacy official in about two 
weeks has one announced opponent in the sept 11 primary 
republican jack sherburne a state representative for eight years 
and a selectman in deerfield for 12 
though humphrey already is looking beyond the primary and general 
election to the internal contest for senate president sherburne 
66 says humphreys candidacy does not faze him 
i think it will make a heck of an interesting race he said 
humphrey is vocally antiabortion sherburne supports abortion 
rights saying society is not wise enough to substitute laws for a 
womans choice 
humphrey says the way to balance budgets is to cut spending 
sherburne says everything should be on the table when new 
hampshire which has no general sales or general income tax writes 
its next budget pinched by a sagging economy and widespread revolts 
against everincreasing property taxes the state is in the midst of 
a debate on tax reform 
rath and others predict that humphrey will face a major 
adjustment away from a multimedia statewide campaign to a 
doortodoor race in one of the states 24 senate districts 
when the media focus goes away what is left for him to work on 
are basically the same issues we spend day in and day out working 
on and they are not as glamorous as those he worked on in 
washington said senate republican leader edward dupont a likely 
senate president candidate 
new hampshires senators usually work three days a week six 
months a year most share office space and the senate has one 
shared media spokesman 
you have to do it on your feet in the state senate rath 
said it is a solitary job youve got to read every bill 
yourself you just dont have a lot of staff to rely on 
humphrey whose annual us senate salary was 98400 
anticipates no trouble adjusting 
i feel very strongly about the importance of state and local 
government and i have no doubt that one can be as fully engaged at 
this level as in the congress he said 
no democrats have announced for the seat but state party 
chairman ned helms said that if humphrey wins the primary the seat 
would become more winable for democrats he called humphrey a 
rightwing zealot far removed from the mainstream of either party 
</TEXT>
