<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev may not have the 
means to carry out a treaty he is expected to sign to destroy soviet 
stocks of chemical weapons 
western officials say that the kremlin last year closed its only 
facility able to carry out the task and has disclosed no plans to 
build another 
there has been no public announcement and the soviets have made 
no communication to the united states on their plans to destroy the 
weapons said a western official involved in the negotiations 
we still have no idea how they plan to do it the official 
said speaking on condition he not be further identified 
top us and soviet leaders have been silent about this curious 
aspect of the chemical weapons pact 
spokesmen at the soviet ministries of defense and foreign affairs 
declined to discuss how they will fulfill the prospective treaty 
which has been touted by us and soviet officials as a highlight of 
the washington summit 
the pact concluded when the us and soviet foreign ministers 
met in moscow in may requires the superpowers to destroy 80 percent 
of their chemical weapons immediately they would reduce their 
stocks to 2 percent of existing levels in the next eight years and 
destroy the rest two years later if all other countries capable of 
producing chemical weapons join them in a global ban officials said 
the united states has an estimated 30000 tons and the soviets 
50000 tons of the weapons according to government sources and 
independent experts 
the us army tested a destruction facility on johnston atoll in 
the pacific ocean this spring and is building similar plants in six 
states 
the soviets built a destruction plant in chapayevsk 550 miles 
southwest of moscow but last summer it fell victim to the growing 
environmental movement 
residents of chapayevsk a center of the soviet chemical 
industry complained the plant would add to already high levels of 
pollution in their city and it was never used 
unable to calm the residents fears soviet officials closed the 
facility and asked the supreme soviet legislature to find a safe 
site to build a new one so far none of the lawmakers has 
volunteered a district for the new plant 
after the chapayevsk facility was closed sheila buckley the top 
pentagon chemical arms negotiator said in a speech that we do not 
believe that they are able right now to destroy the amount they 
claim to have which is 50000 tons there is no indication the 
situation has changed us analysts say 
us rep larry hopkins rky visited the chapayevsk site last 
summer and suggested to secretary of state james a baker iii and 
soviet defense minister dmitry t yazov that the united states share 
technology with the soviets to destroy the weapons 
the soviets are more inclined to go that route than the 
americans but have not made any concrete requests the western 
official said 
a soviet foreign ministry spokesman yuri a gremitskykh 
declined to disclose his governments plans for destroying the 
chemicals 
now there will be negotiations on this issue between the 
presidents and experts and ministers and we hope there will be a 
written agreement and then then we will give you an answer about 
how we will be destroying these agreed upon quantities of chemical 
weapons gremitskykh said 
five officials in the press office of the soviet ministry of 
defense declined to discuss soviet plans to destroy chemical 
weapons they referred a reporter to a ministry of foreign affairs 
official who asked for a letter requesting an interview on the 
subject 
baker after meeting in moscow with gorbachev and soviet foreign 
minister eduard a shevardnadze was euphoric on announcing the 
makings of the deal may 19 
we have reached agreement on a precedentsetting accord 
baker told reporters we believe that this agreement is very 
significant particularly as it provides a real pathway toward a 
global ban on horrific weapons that we already know from bitter 
experience actually get used 
the soviet plan for the chapayevsk plant had been to destroy two 
chemicals also found in the us arsenal the nerve agents sarin and 
vx by mixing them with caustic agents and burning the residue 
according to soviet press reports 
the us army used similar means to destroy mustard agents in 
197475 but discarded the method because it left toxic waste the 
head of the american program gen walter l busbee said in an 
interview earlier this year 
the sites in the united states where the government will destroy 
its chemical weapons are in maryland kentucky alabama utah 
indiana oregon arkansas and utah the technology tested at 
johnston atoll to be used at other sites burns the chemicals at 
2700 degrees and filters the exhaust 
