one in five minority college students are the 
victims of racial attacks and former president reagans policies 
are at least partly to blame says a group that tracks such 
incidents 
reagan spokesman mark weinberg said however that cheap 
political fingerpointing wont bring a solution to the problem 
as many as 1 million college students are victims each year of 
attacks that range from verbal slurs to physical assaults officials 
of the national institute against prejudice and violence said 
thursday 
if we had an incidence of disease at 20 percent the surgeon 
general would have declared a public health crisis howard j 
ehrlich research director for the fiveyearold group said at a 
news conference 
representatives of the group said attacks on homosexual students 
appear to be even more frequent 
ehrlich said most college students came of political age 
during the reagan presidency when civil rights were being devalued 
in this society 
the report campus ethnoviolence and the policy options said 
minority students at predominantly white campuses suffer almost 
constant pressures because of their ethnic backgrounds 
for most students there are times when the classroom 
atmosphere can be stressful for the minority students stress and 
discomfort may be an everyday occurrence the report said 
ehrlich said figures show that between 800000 and 1 million 
students are victimized each year a quarter of those he said have 
been harassed on more than one occasion 
former democratic sen birch bayh of indiana chairman of the 
institutes board of directors said reagan did nothing during his 
eight years in the white house to set a proper tone for racial 
tolerance in the country 
there was absolutely no leadership during the reagan 
administration to show this nation how it could be better bayh 
said at the news conference the president is supposed to stand up 
and say we dont tolerate this in the united states of america 
bayh said what reagan did do on civil rights was negative 
such as the former presidents push to dismantle the us civil 
rights commission and his opposition to the extension of the voting 
rights act of 1964 
bayh said president bush already has taken positive steps to deal 
with the problem such as inviting various groups to the signing 
ceremony for the hate crimes reporting act but bushs term is too 
new to assess his record on civil rights bayh added 
while bush has spoken against racial insensitivity wed like 
to see more than words bayh said 
weinberg reached by telephone in los angeles discounted bayhs 
claims saying to ronald reagan there is no greater sin than 
prejudice 
belief in the quality of all men and women has been at the very 
core of his soul throughout his life those who think otherwise are 
ignorant weinberg said 
the spokesman said reagan is very troubled by incidents of 
racial bigotry on college campuses and elsewhere and believes the 
solution will be found not by cheap political fingerpointing but 
through dialogue and sincere efforts to increase understanding 
