<TEXT>
strong aftershocks rocked jungle villages 
in northern peru sending terrified residents into streets and town 
squares two days after a killer earthquake rocked the region the 
death toll rose to at least 137 
hundreds of people whose homes were damaged slept on towels and 
mats thursday in the streets of rioja and moyobamba the two largest 
towns in the affected area about 400 miles north of lima 
the quake destroyed between 30 and 40 percent of the buildings in 
the area the civil defense office in lima said 
civil defense officials in the earthquake zone said at least 137 
people died in tuesdays earthquake which measured 63 on the 
richter scale 
the government daily la cronica however said more than 200 were 
killed the differing figures could not immediately be reconciled 
perus geophysical institute in lima said at least 70 aftershocks 
had struck since tuesday night including one thursday morning that 
registered 46 on the richter scale 
all the tremors were centered around moyobamba a farming 
community of 50000 that produces corn rice coffee and sugar cane 
