<DOCNO> AP900601-0071 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us officials are asking japan to help pick up the 
tab for an 8 billion superconducting supercollider that could 
answer basic questions about th nature of matter and the origin of 
the universe 
deputy secretary of energy henson moore who is heading a 
visiting us delegation told reporters he would present a letter 
from president bush to prime minister toshiki kaifu inviting japan 
to become a partner in the supercollider project to be built in 
texas 
we have asked japan to be the first country to participate 
because of their technical expertise and also because they have 
the capability of being a partner moore said 
the size and the expense of building this project is such that 
no one country can do it alone he added and we believe that 
for it to be a scientific success it must be an international 
project 
moore did not specify the amount the us government wants japan 
to contribute the kyodo news service reported that the united 
states wants japan to allocate 1 billion for the project 
backers say the racetrackshaped supercollider which would 
encircle waxahachie texas with a 54mile tunnel would be the 
worlds most powerful particle accelerator and its largest 
scientific instrument 
the department of energy says the supercolliders 12000 
superconducting magnets will produce a magnetic field 150000 times 
as strong as earths and send streams of protons smashing against 
each other at nearly the speed of light to break them into subatomic 
particles 
scientists then would study the tiny pieces of matter produced in 
hopes of finding previously unobservable particlesthat would provide 
clues to how the universe began 
scientists say such intensely powerful collisions will 
approximate the big bang explosion that some believe created the 
universe 
the cost of the project has grown from an initial 44 billion to 
about 8 billion 
earlier this month the us house of representatives authorized 
5 billion in spending over several years on the supercollider and 
texas agreed to provide about 1 billion to get the project 
the government hopes that the remaining 2 billion will come 
largely from foreign sources department of energy officials said 
some us congressmen have demanded japan bear a large portion of 
the cost because of its trade imbalance with the united states but 
others have warned that foreign involvement would result in a giving 
away us technology 
moore said the united states wanted japan as a partner because of 
its ability to contribute both scientifically and financially to the 
project 
moore said japan also has shown an understanding of the need to 
spend more on basic research 
japan spends less of its gross national product than the united 
states on basic scientific research but more on applied research 
it frequently has taken the discoveries of basic research conducted 
elsewhere and developed them into new consumer products 
participation in research projects at the superconducting 
supercollider would be open to any nation regardless of whether it 
helps fund it as is true with most such particle accelerators 
moore said 
department of energy officials said up to half the accelerators 
magnets could be provided by japan which already has developed a 
prototype of a magnetically levitated train that uses 
superconducting magnets 
each cylindrical magnet will be 45feetlong and weigh 132 tons 
the department says 
after a week in japan the us delegation is to visit south 
korea to seek its participation in the project the only country 
that has already officially agreed to participate is india which 
pledged 50 million 
the worlds most powerful collider is a 17mile ring near geneva 
that was completed last year 
the us delegation here made the funding request at meetings 
with education minister kosuke hori tomoji oshima director general 
of the science and technology agency and ichiji ishii deputy 
foreign minister 
</TEXT>
