thursday but judged it too small to have been the source of the 
hydrogen leak that delayed wednesday mornings launch buckingham 
said 
after the launch was scrubbed officials had said it would take 
at least a week that is until next wednesday to find and repair 
the leak and prepare for another launch now with continuing 
problems finding the leak the launch is off at least until the week 
after that bukingham said 
the search continued until late thursday afternoon then was 
halted so columbias onboard fuel tanks could be drained officials 
today further increased pressure on the shuttles external tank 
which was drained of fuel and filled with nonflammable helium to 
find the main leak 
engineers are now fairly certain the leak is in or near a 17inch 
valve in a pipe that carries fuel from the shuttles external tank 
to its main engines buckingham said traces of helium were found 
early today in a tight cavity between two metal plates that connect 
the shuttle and its external tank he said 
if the leak is in that cavity it would be an extremely 
difficult area to repair at the pad buckingham said but 
nothing at this point has been ruled out 
if the leak is not pinpointed today helium may be circulated 
through the shuttles entire fuel system saturday buckingham said 
the next step would be to use supercold liquid hydrogen in an 
attempt to duplicate the conditions under which the leak was 
detected six hours before launch while liquid hydrogen and oxygen 
were being loaded 
preparations were under way for the liquid hydrogen test which 
is scheduled for the middle of next week buckingham said 
columbias astronomy mission with a 150 million observatory 
called astro already had been delayed two weeks for repairs to the 
shuttles cooling system 
