<TEXT>
guatemalan rebels and nine political parties 
reached agreement today on moves aimed at ending 28 years of armed 
conflict in the central american nation 
a joint statement released after five days of talks in a hotel 
outside madrid said the rebel guatamalan national revolutionary 
union will join the parties in an assembly next year to revise 
guatemalas constitution 
the political parties represented at the talks including the 
christian democrats of president vinicio cerezo accepted the 
guerrillas demand that paramilitary civil patrols be disbanded and 
that the armed forces subjected to increased political control 
in todays statement the guerrillas pledged not to disrupt 
guatemalas general elections set for november however a rebel 
spokesman said this would not mean a general ceasefire in the 
fighting 
the statement was released at a news conference after closeddoor 
talks in el escorial 25 miles north of madrid 
the agreement is expected to serve as a framework for future 
negotiations among the guerrillas cerezos government and top 
military officers 
before then the guerrillas are likely to open talks with 
representatives of guatemalan trade unions businessmen and the 
roman catholic church a rebel spokesman said this week 
the guatemalan conflict set off by rebel army officiers in 1962 
has claimed between 30000 and 60000 lives according to government 
estimates 
the rebels say 100000 people have died and that 50000 are 
missing 
a first round of peace talks held in 1987 in madrid ended in 
deadlock 
this weeks negotiations were moderated by the sixmember 
national reconciliation council headed by guatemala archbishop 
rodolfo quesado un official francesc vendrell attended the 
meeting as an observer 
three rebel leaders took part in the negotiations including 
veteran guerrilla chief rodrigo asturias also known by the code 
name cmdr gaspar 
the party leaders included former guatemalan vicepresident mario 
sandoval founder of the ultraconservative national liberation 
movement 
the negotiations form part of a process begun after the 1987 
esquipulas ii central american peace accords the regions five 
presidents agreed that conflicts in their central american nations 
should be ended through democratic reforms and political 
negotiations between governments and rebel movements 
the united states has expressed support for the guatemalan talks 
</TEXT>
