the justice department said friday it wont 
appeal the sentence of a suspended cornell university graduate 
student placed on probation for paralyzing a nationwide computer 
network 
the justice department which had sought a prison term for robert 
t morris jr decided last month not to appeal the lighter sentence 
imposed may 4 by a federal judge in syracuse ny 
the decision was made after a recommendation by assistant 
attorney general edward sg dennis jr head of the criminal 
division officials said 
morris 23 convicted of unleashing a computer virus in 1988 that 
immobilized 6000 computers linked to a government network was 
placed on three years probation fined 10000 and ordered to 
perform 400 hours of community service 
the son of a government computer scientist morris was the first 
person convicted under the 1986 computer fraud and abuse act he was 
found guilty in january of breaking and entering the internet 
computer network by designing and unleashing a computer virus 
under procedures that took effect in 1987 both the prosecution 
and defense may appeal the judges sentence justice officials felt 
prosecutors made their point by obtaining the felony conviction 
said spokesman doug tillett 
in terms of deterrent value our point was made by the fact we 
brought the case tillett said it was up to the discretion of 
the judge to mete out a proper sentence 
justice officials regarded morris as a bright kid who shouldnt 
have done what he did tillett said the case was seen as an 
important test of the computer fraud law 
the defense argued that the government was overreacting in 
trying to brand morris a criminal 
morris lawyers said their client didnt benefit from the 
computer virus noting that others convicted of such crimes had 
stolen money 
morris testified that the computer virus which he admitted 
designing to invade internet was an experiment that got out of 
control 
prosecutors contended that morris carefully plotted an assault on 
the nationwide network of government military and university 
computers that was disabled in november 1988 by the virus that 
originated from morris computer at cornell 
defense lawyer thomas guidoboni said he was pleased about the 
governments decision not to appeal 
morris suspended from cornells graduate program in computer 
science must apply for readmission if he wants to return guidoboni 
said 
