<TEXT>
charles taylor the useducated rebel 
leader whose army bore down on the capital this week is a former 
bureaucrat who speaks enthusiastically about capitalism but not 
democracy 
taylor denies government allegations he embezzled 1 million 
while he ran the general services administration liberias 
purchasing agency he is wanted in the united states for escaping 
custody pending extradition to liberia 
taylor 42 spent the 1970s working as a mechanic at a plastics 
factory in boston before graduating with an economics degree from 
bentley college in waltham mass 
during those years taylor says he headed an organization of 
35000 liberian exiles in the united states he said they were 
working to overthrow the rule of his country by the descendants of 
freed american slaves who founded the nation in 1847 
taylor returned to liberia after samuel doe took power in a 1979 
military coup giving the indigenous population control of the west 
african country for the first time in its history 
doe named taylor head of the general services administration 
taylor fled to the united states in 1983 to escape charges of 
embezzlement 
he was arrested in the united states but escaped before he could 
be extradited 
i skipped from jail to escape does lies taylor has said he 
said all charges would be dropped if he toppled does government 
taylors revolt began dec 24 1989 when he crossed the ivory 
coast border into liberia with a small band of men they accused doe 
of corruption mismanagement and human rights abuses 
taylor based his men in nimba county an area traditionally 
hostile to doe 
does forces responded with savage attacks on tribal groups that 
supported taylor international agencies say hundreds were killed 
and the atrocities appeared to have increased support for taylor 
taylor has made good use of the news media making frequent 
telephone calls to the british broadcasting corp and other news 
organizations 
last month he gave a news conference for foreign journalists in 
tapeta in the heart of rebelheld territory about 100 miles 
northeast of monrovia the capital 
the bearded rebel said he wanted to assure the united states 
liberias main foreign aid donor that he was committed to good 
relations 
the united states has permanent interests in liberia and not 
permanent friends he said i would hope that we would have a 
real good marriage and a real honeymoon 
but his declarations on democracy have provided little cheer to 
the opposition parties that had been contesting does power taylor 
said he wouldnt share power with opposition parties 
dont think we are going to turn the government over to someone 
to screw up he said 
he said his plans do not include elections for at least three 
years and perhaps five years 
as a civilian however taylor insists he is different from doe 
who made his career in the military he said he was leading a 
grassroots civilian uprising to get rid of a dictator but 
harbored no dictatorial ambitions himself 
it is so easy to make a dictator in liberia and i am not going 
to permit myself to be one he has promised 
 
taylor describes himself as a churchgoing christian and 
pledges to restore traditional christian values 
before liberians were interested in school in church he 
said nobody thinks of going to church anymore everybody talks of 
ritualistic killings 
the vast majority of the countrys 25 million people practice 
traditional african beliefs black magic or juju is widely 
practiced 
taylor wears two woven amulets around his neck his guerrillas 
say the amulets are magic charms that protect the wearer from 
bullets 
