<TEXT>
oliver north testified friday before a newly 
empaneled federal grand jury that is continuing the investigation of 
the irancontra scandal 
the former white house aide was accompanied into the grand jury 
room by a prosecutor from the office of independent counsel lawrence 
walsh 
north repeatedly left the secret proceedings during an entire day 
of testimony to confer with his attorneys in a courthouse hallway 
periodic exits from grand jury proceedings enable witnesses to 
receive legal advice and to keep their lawyers informed about what 
areas of questioning the government is interested 
during one break north lawyer brendan sullivan began shouting at 
irancontra prosecutor craig gillen 
you dont intimidate me and i dont intimidate you replied 
gillen who then returned to the grand jury room north followed a 
few minutes later 
walshs office is trying to determine the precise roles that 
thenpresident reagan thenvice president bush and others played in 
the affair sources familiar with the investigation said in april 
the sources speaking on condition of anonymity said north and 
former national security adviser john poindexter were likely to be 
subpoenaed and granted immunity from prosecution in exchange for 
their grand jury testimony 
north appearedn federal court a week ago in a closed session for 
which all records are under seal 
the grand jury delving into the scandal began meeting last month 
after poindexters april felony convictions 
walshs office has repeatedly refused to make any comment on the 
latest phase of its 3yearold investigation 
irancontra prosecutors have had more than a year to pore over 
about 2800 pages of notebooks that north kept while he worked at 
the national security council 
the daily notebook entries refer to occasional meetings with bush 
and reagan they also refer to dozens of contacts with cia officers 
such as alan fiers and state department officials such as elliott 
abrams who kept track of the nicaraguan contras 
north 46 was convicted may 4 1989 of aiding and abetting an 
obstruction of congress altering and destroying national security 
council documents and receiving an illegal gratuity 
an appeal of his convictions is pending before the us court of 
appeals 
poindexter convicted in april of conspiracy obstructing 
congress and making false statements in the scandal is scheduled to 
be sentenced june 11 the former national security adviser faces up 
to 25 years in prison and 125 million in fines 
 
