plainclothes police who made little attempt to hide their 
walkietalkies milled in the crowd but only one uniformed officer 
walked up to the demonstrators and asked them to disperse the 
officer walked away when protesters showed that they had applied to 
the authorities to hold the rally 
they held up posters and unfurled banners that said refuseniks 
are the hostages of perestroika and shame on antisemitism 
our demonstration is synchronized with a demonstration in 
washington we insist that our human rights are violated said 
mike shapiro he said he has been denied an emigration visa even 
though he stopped his secret work for the soviet government more 
than 12 years ago 
stephen cohen of palm beach fla a member of the board of 
directors of the union of councils for soviet jews said there are 
400 to 500 families of jews who have been refused permission to 
emigrate because soviet officials say they have knowledge of state 
secrets 
in november the supreme soviet legislature gave preliminary 
approval to a bill that allows emigration for virtually anyone who 
has entry permission from another country and no outstanding alimony 
obligations criminal charges or recent knowledge of state secrets 
it sets a limit of five years on the period a citizen can be kept 
from emigrating because of access to secrets 
but jewish activists claim that the bill is vaguely worded and 
might still be used to restrict emigration 
the bill has not yet come up for a final vote the united states 
is withholding action on loosening trade sanctions on the soviet 
union until the immigration law is passed 
leonid stonov one longtime refusenik who was told in recent 
weeks that he will be allowed to emigrate in august said 
antisemitism is on the rise and that he sees a difficult future for 
jews in the soviet union 
all the jewish culture jewish tradition jewish life 
everything was ruined here during the stalin era and brezhnev era 
there is no basement no foundation for establishing here a real 
jewish life he said 
mark m kotlyar a refusenik from kiev was asked how he felt 
when he saw president mikhail s gorbachev cheered on the streets of 
washington this week he smiled and said it was a difficult question 
to answer 
on the one hand its important that people be friendly that 
they meet our leaders that they give them a warm reception 
kotlyar said but on the other hand i think that they are too 
rapturous about gorbachev he is not that good he is not 
pamela braun cohen national president of the union of councils 
for soviet jews acknowledged that gorbachev has brought change to 
the soviet union 
the fact that we are here holding this demonstration today and 
the fact that the people who have held the demonstration were not 
taken away you cant dismiss it she said 
but she said the american public needs to be more tempered in 
its approach to gorbachev and that might better serve the human 
rights movement here in this country and better serve the united 
states in their relationship with the soviets 
