five former agriculture secretaries and more 
than two dozen farmrelated groups called friday for an upgrading of 
trade ties with the soviet union so far resisted by the bush 
administration 
there is a large potential for further development of this 
market to the mutual benefit of the united states and the soviet 
union said the statement 
it came as soviet president mikhail s gorbachev was visiting the 
united states and followed a meeting at which gorbachev urged 
cooperation from members of congress who have resisted granting 
moscow better trade ties 
the statement called for granting the soviets mostfavorednation 
status which would give them the same preferential tariffs given 
the united states other top trading partners 
the soviet union was the second largest singlenation importer of 
us farm products last year buying a record 36 billion 
president bush said recently it was too early to grant 
mostfavorednation status to the soviets although he recently 
renewed that standing for the chinese despite protests over last 
years bloody crackdown in tiananmen square 
trade negotiations are currently under way between the united 
states and the soviets 
an important part of that agreement would be 
mostfavorednation status for the soviets giving the soviets the 
same access to our market as enjoyed by most of our trading 
partners the statement said 
the signers included former agriculture secretaries john r 
block orville l freeman earl l butz bob bergland and richard e 
lyng 
the statement was issued by national agricultural advisory 
committee of the citizens network for foreign affairs whose 
directors include former top government officials as well as 
business and labor leaders 
while mfn will not solve the soviet unions economic problems 
it would help to build a relationship that all sides can count on 
for the long term and be a basis for bringing the soviet union more 
fully into the world trading system the statement said 
it did say that to strengthen trade and investment ties between 
our two countries the soviet union must continue to expand 
individual freedom including the right of selfdetermination and 
emigration and reach a peaceful and equitable resolution of the 
baltic situation 
other signers ranged from the american farm bureau federation to 
the national farmers union to cargill inc the agricultural 
exportimport giant they included producer groups specializing in 
meat oats soybeans wheat corn pork and rice 
