<TEXT>
west germany and luxembourg joined france on friday 
in banning british beef imports because of mad cow disease but 
the european community offered to buy british meat to support that 
nations troubled cattle industry 
france which normally purchases more than half of exported 
british beef imposed a ban wednesday it said some meat might be 
tainted by bovine spongiform encephalopathy an incurable and fatal 
nervous disorder 
the disease identified in britain in 1986 is blamed for killing 
13648 cows there 
west germany had already barred imports of british beef still on 
the bone but followed france by extending the ban to canned beef 
friday 
luxembourg later announced a ban on british beef imports said an 
ec commission spokesman in brussels 
west germanys agriculture ministry said in bonn that it feared 
british beef normally destined for france might be rerouted to west 
germany a ban was necessary to protect consumers from 
infection the ministry said 
but british officials accused france and germany of seeking to 
protect their domestic beef industries and exaggerating their 
concern for public health 
the bans are totally unjustified unwarranted and contrary to 
ec law said britains ministry of agriculture spokesman 
the president of britains national farmers union sir simon 
gourlay called for a retaliatory ban of beef imports from all eec 
countries to bring the community to its senses 
we cannot allow the situation to drag on through cynical 
delaying tactics by some other governments he said 
european community officials denounced frances ban thursday as 
illegal and demanded it be revoked 
in brussels belgium ec headquarters said friday the community 
would buy 20600 tons of british beef to help prop up falling meat 
prices 
the british meat and livestock commission said bans and fears 
arising from mad cow disease were costing their industry about 
850000 a day beef sales reportedly have fallen by about 30 
percent in britain 
a team of french veterinarians sent to britain to assess mad 
cow disease returned friday to submit its report frances 
agriculture ministry said no decision on the duration of the ban 
would be made until after a meeting of the european communitys 
veterinary committee 
however british agriculture officials said the committee meeting 
had been postponed indefinitely 
the cause of mad cow disease is unknown because the symptoms 
are similar to scrapie a sheep disease it is assumed the disease 
was transmitted through cattle feeds they use sheep offal as a 
protein supplement 
