<TEXT>
art treasures from five centuries of russian 
history and culture from the medieval to the avantgarde go on 
display saturday in their first exhibition outside the soviet union 
more than 250 items are in moscow treasures and traditions 
which runs through sept 30 at the washington state convention and 
trade center 
the unique collection compiled from the kremlin soviet state 
museums and artists studios includes icons engravings metalwork 
porcelain and historic costumes which have played important roles 
in russian history some highlights are 
a 15th century icon miracle of st george and the dragon 
executed in egg tempera on wood 
a 17th century suit of chain mail armor and an early musket 
an altar cross donated to a monastery by ivan the terrible and a 
helmet belonging to his son 
the exhibit is making its world premiere here as the largest 
component of the goodwill arts festival an international cultural 
bash coinciding with this summers goodwill games 
with the many athletes coming from the soviet union we wanted 
to give the american public a broader understanding of this world 
power we know little about said c david hughbanks managing 
director of the exhibition 
weve come to expect socalled socialist art where the 
russian tradition is concerned this show offers a much broader 
perspective a whole history of the people of moscow 
the collection illustrates historical events in russian life in 
seven separate themes including the significance and place of 
christianity in 15th century russian society other themes portray 
the hopes dreams and realities of soviet life including the 
desire for social reform 
the exhibit is a celebration and a tribute to a city and its 
people as seen through the eyes of artists and craftsmen most of 
whom are little known to the western world hughbanks said 
officials from the soviet ministry of culture and from four of 
the 20 museums which lent their works to the exhibit accompanied the 
art to seattle 
the exhibit will be displayed at the smithsonian institution in 
washington dc beginning in november before returning to the 
soviet union in february 1991 
</TEXT>
