<TEXT>
president bush and mikhail s gorbachev hit 
lastminute snags on a landmark nuclear weapons agreement friday as 
the soviet leader pressed fervently for us concessions on trade 
nevertheless they were ready to sign an agreement slashing chemical 
weapon stockpiles 
the unexpected impediments to the arms agreement marred an 
outwardly friendly summit and spokesmen said they were hopeful the 
problems could be worked out secretary of state james a baker iii 
and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze were called in to 
troubleshoot 
the second day of superpower summitry appeared marked by tough 
bargaining by gorbachev missing from a white house list of 
agreements to be signed were the arms accord a grainsale agreement 
sought by american farmers and the trade treaty that gorbachev wants 
senate republican leader bob dole who met with gorbachev said 
the soviet leader desperately wants some give on the trade side 
however he said congress was equally insistent that lithuania must 
win freedom from moscow before making economic concessions 
i think he feels that if he doesnt get it hes going home 
emptyhanded dole said gorbachev besieged by mounting economic 
problems said a gesture on trade would be useful for him at home 
both sides expressed confidence that the outlines of an agreement 
for the firstever reductions in longrange nuclear weapons would be 
signed before the summit ends on sunday 
bush and gorbachev themselves hinted at difficulties after their 
morning talks but their relaxed demeanor gave no indication of 
major stumbling blocks 
we always have complications but we measure it not by the glass 
as halfempty or the glass is half full bush said at his side 
gorbachev said they had made a lot of progress 
despite problems with a strategic weapons pact the leaders were 
ready to sign the separate accord imposing a halt in production of 
chemical weapons and requiring the two nations to cut their poison 
gas stockpiles to 5000 tons each 
bush and gorbachev also were unable to make progress on cutting 
troops and nonnuclear weapons in europe they issued a statement 
declaring early conclusion of an agreement was essential to 
the future stability and security of the continent 
bush had initially hoped to extract a commitment from gorbachev 
at this weeks summit on conventional arms cutbacks but differences 
between the two sides remained 
on a related front sources said gorbachev trying to break a 
stalemate had proposed creation of a new council of all europe 
to play a decisive role in shaping the military future of germany 
the united states and the soviet union would participate in the 
deliberations along with other members of the nato and warsaw pact 
alliances as well as neutral countries 
a us official said we are prepared to work with it it is 
not something we would reject out of hand the idea will be 
considered by top diplomatic aides in copenhagen and berlin later 
this month 
the second day of summitry was punctuated by gorbachev scolding 
congressional leaders for stalling trade benefits for moscow 
we are not asking for a free ride gorbachev said he said it 
would be humilitating to beg for concessions 
a trade treaty would be a politically important symbol for 
gorbachev burdened by deepening economic woes us officials said 
the soviets were holding hostage an agreement to buy american grain 
a boost to us farmers as a bargaining chip for the trade deal 
gorbachev said a gesture from the united states on trade would be 
especially politically useful for him at home the united states 
wants the soviets to ease pressure on breakaway lithuania and 
guarantee protection for jewish emigration 
by itself a trade agreement has little value however it is 
part of a package leading to mostfavorednation trade status which 
would drastically reduce us tariffs on soviet goods 
the superpower summit was spiced with colorful sideshows barbara 
bush and raisa gorbachev were cheered at wellesley college 
commencement exercises and gorbachev once again stopped his 
entourage to work the noonhour crowds on a brilliant sunny day 
both women spoke of traditional values at wellesley mrs bush 
whose selection as a graduation speaker had irritated some students 
counseled them to put family and friends first in their lives mrs 
gorbachev said women have a special mission of peacemaking 
humanism mercy and kindness 
gorbachev began the day by confronting some of his toughest 
critics in washington congressional leaders unhappy over moscows 
coercion of lithuania the baltic republic struggling for 
independence televised live across america it was a freewheeling 
exchange over trade german unity lithuania and soviet economic 
reforms 
gorbachev took the offensive he said bush was too rigid about 
insisting that a unified germany be a member of nato and rejected 
any suggestion that he was politically weak thats not serious 
he said 
this is a genuine revolution gorbachev told the lawmakers 
some of whom have expressed doubts that he will survive please 
dont be frightened because you can frighten us too if you get 
frightened 
extolling his economic reforms gorbachev said increased trade 
with the west would be an important step toward a free market system 
in the soviet union 
however gorbachev lectured im not going to ask for anything 
to beg for anything certainly we are not asking for a free 
ride we will be asking for normal credits and of course we will be 
paying and paying the interest for us it would humiliating if we 
were to ask to beg for something from you 
when congressmen pressed him on lithuania gorbachev pointed out 
that china had received mostfavorednation status despite the 
bloody crackdown in tiananmen square a year ago maybe we should 
introduce martial rule in the baltics he said sarcastically 
the agreement on strategic weapons the deadliest arms in the 
superpowers arsenals has been under negotiation for eight years 
it would be the first to reduce longrange nuclear arms previous 
agreements set overall limits but still allowed more weapons to be 
made 
even after both sides initial a treaty outline the superpowers 
will face months of tedious negotiations over details to satisfy 
lawyers in each country 
overall both sides would agree to destroy about a third of their 
longrange nuclear weapons over seven years 
the chemical weapons pact would require the united states to 
destroy about 20000 tons of its stockpile and mandate a 45000 ton 
reduction by the soviet union the united states also would be 
required to stop producing poison gas the soviet union already has 
stopped 
along with the arms agreements there also were accords expanding 
air travel between the united states and soviet union increasing 
student exchanges and making it easier for commercial ships to 
deliver goods to ports in one anothers country 
there was an agreement for closer cooperation on atomic energy 
and another to open reciprocal cultural and information centers in 
washington and moscow 
