<TEXT>
as if testifying in his own defense president 
mikhail s gorbachev held forth for an hourandhalf friday 
answering congressional questioners on everything from the 
lithuanian embargo to the price of soviet bread 
he reasoned with them cajoled lectured confessed and just 
hours after his stunning televised performance he won from 
president bush the trade agreement he had hoped to take home from 
the summit 
it is still subject to congressional approval and the lawmakers 
suggested that wouldnt come easily as long as the soviet embargo on 
lithuania remains in effect 
the pact wouldnt have an instant impact gorbachev told the 
lawmakers he had invited to breakfast at the soviet embassy but it 
would open the way for american business people to participate in 
the soviet unions economic development 
you should do some rethinking of how to act so as not to impede 
trade he told the leaders arguing that a soviet union which is 
weak torn by complexes and problems and turmoil is more 
threatening to the united states than a dynamic soviet state that 
is open to the outside world 
he admitted that when he launched perestroika five years ago he 
thought he could fix the communist system with some tinkering such 
as adding private cooperatives and permitting farm leasing but it 
didnt work 
really we were being very naive he said in our system 
it was just impossible there was no incentive there was no 
motivation for people to work 
but to change the economic system he said he had to institute 
democracy to create pressure on the authorities to change 
that proved so effective that in some regions the entire 
ruling structures were swept aside by the political wave and the 
old system was dismantled before a new one could be put in place 
our ship has lost anchor and therefore were all a little 
sick the president said describing the present confusion and 
turmoil in his country he said that if the government doesnt move 
quickly to establish the new marketoriented economy he has 
proposed the whole society will suffer 
gorbachev laid out for his congressional audience the enormity of 
his task involving creation of new forms of ownership including 
private property once considered anathema to communists 
we need competitiveness in our economy and that is why we will 
be adopting laws on entrepreneurship on small and mediumsize 
business we do not have a system of markets we do not have systems 
of stock exchanges monetary or labor exchanges so we have to be 
developing an entire infrastucture for the market 
tripling the price of bread even before the market is in place as 
an unpopular step he conceded but he insisted that bread is so 
cheap and plentiful in the soviet union that kids play football 
with loaves of bread feed bread to cattle and its really 
outrageous 
congress has urged president bush not to sign a trade agreement 
with the soviet union until it lifts its embargo of lithuania which 
has declared its independence 
in an exhaustive account of the lithuanian crisis and his efforts 
to solve it gorbachev said the lithuanian parliament had rushed its 
own election process and staged a nighttime coup detat to 
secede from the union 
similar pressures exist in many soviet republics he said and 
lithuania cant be dealt with alone ignoring its own minority 
nationalities and territorial claims by other republics 
gorbachev described himself as taking a conciliatory stance 
willing to negotiate with the lithuanians and work out procedures 
for eventual independence but he insisted the republic must submit 
to a popular referendum and respect the rights of its ethnic 
minorities including russians and poles 
he chided congress for permitting bush to invade panama 
suggesting that move also was unconstitutional and failed to respect 
the popular will of the panamanians 
sen george j mitchell dmaine interrupted with a retort that 
there are very significant differences in the two situations and 
suggesting the lithuanian declaration like the panama invasion 
had overwhelming popular support 
all right all right he said fine fine fine let them 
do it and well agree but only through a constitutional process 
asked to explain why the soviet legislature had not yet adopted a 
law liberalizing emigration gorbachev protested that the us 
congress was getting too deeply involved in his countrys domestic 
affairs 
this is a matter of dignity this is a matter of prestige this 
is a matter of sovereignty and national dignity so please be 
careful about this he said but he went on to answer the 
question saying the emigration law has been adopted on first 
reading its provisions are in effect if you look at the 
reality of the situation its provisions are in effect the flow of 
emigres from soviet union is practically not braked you know that 
this is no longer a problem 
he suggested congress was looking for a pretext in order to put 
a brake on this process of adopting mostfavorednation treatment 
that would lower tariff barriers for soviet products sold in the 
united states 
asked how congress could help gorbachev pleaded for a 
favorable gesture on trade and he asked for extension of credit 
to finance joint ventures and the conversion to a market economy 
making it easier for us during this difficult period he 
promised to start paying back the money within seven years 
he accused the united states of applying a double standard by 
withholding mfn status from the soviet union while granting it to 
china after the crushing of the democratic movement in tiananmen 
square 
maybe we should introduce presidential rule in the baltics and 
at least fire some rounds he suggested wryly 
