<TEXT>
the united states and the soviet union on 
friday reached agreement to ban heavy mobile nuclear missiles under 
the treaty they are negotiating on longrange nuclear weapons 
in addition they also agreed on an extensive verification system 
to ensure the reductions in a wide range of deadly weapons are 
carried out 
a joint statement issued at the midpoint of president bushs 
summit meeting with soviet president mikhail s gorbachev called 
also for acceleration of negotiations in geneva to complete the 
start treaty by the end of the year 
at the white house bush and gorbachev approved the outlines of 
the landmark treaty friday for the firstever cuts in longrange 
nuclear missiles 
secretary of state james a baker iii said that major issues had 
been settled and completion of the treaty by the end of the year was 
likely 
agreement on a ban on heavy mobile missiles marked an expansion 
of the limitations already agreed to in eight years of ussoviet 
talks 
the verification procedure will cover 12 kinds of onsite 
inspections some of them on short notice 
the agreement would prevent the soviets from putting their heavy 
groundbased ss18 missiles on mobile launchers such as trains or 
trucks a senior us official said 
the ban would have no direct impact on current us nuclear 
forces but would prevent the united states from basing any future 
heavy intercontinental missile on mobile launchers 
the official who briefed reporters on details under rules that 
he not be identified said americas mx missile would not be 
restricted in any way under the agreement because it is not 
considered a heavy missile 
among the existing icbms in both nations arsenals only the ss18 
will be included in the banned category 
the farreaching reductions and other constraints contained in 
the treaty will be accompanied by the most thorough and innovative 
verification provisions ever negotiated the ussoviet statement 
said 
baker said both sides had made a commitment in a second round of 
negotiations to make cuts in heavy missiles and those with multiple 
warheads 
on the other hand baker said at a news conference serious 
substantive differences remain on reducing troops tanks and other 
nonnuclear weapons from europe that would not be resolved at the 
summit 
in short i think weve made workmanlike progress across the 
range of ussoviet relations he said 
baker said the negotiations that were conducted since sunday 
expanded on the nuclear weapons categories to be restricted in the 
treaty in addition to adding the limits on mobile missiles he said 
the presidents had reached an agreement on the goals and 
objectives of future negotiations to make even deeper cuts 
particularly in overall numbers of warheads 
still baker said they failed to resolve disagreements over the 
soviet backfire bomber flight tests of heavy groundbased missiles 
and safeguards against the transfer of nuclear weaponry to third 
countries 
