the superpowers are billing their nearly 
completed arms treaty as a step toward ending the arms race but 
private experts said friday its value may be mainly symbolic 
the deal as outlined by president bush and soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev carries a potent political punch its the 
first treaty to reduce the number of longrange nuclear arms 
but by the time the pact is fully implemented probably in 1998 
analysts say both the united states and the soviet union may be 
nearly asth nuclear arms as they are today unless 
additional treaties are negotiated be well stocked wifore then 
gorbachev and bush failed in a second day of summitry friday to 
settle at least three points of dispute in the proposed treaty but 
they pledged to conclude the deal by the end of the year they also 
agreed to begin negotiating a followup treaty on strategic arms 
once the pending deal is finished 
the military significance of the emerging agreement is diluted by 
decisions to discount or exclude some weapons from the 
counting rules and to leavthe natural resources defense 
council a private research group described the treaty as making a 
virtue of necessity scrapping mostly obsolete weapons while 
permitting both sides to continue building new ones 
everything is allowed just at slightly reduced numbers he 
said 
among the us weapons that are expected to be scrapped under the 
start treaty if completed in its current form and ratified by both 
countries legislatures are minuteman ii intercontinental ballistic 
missiles deployed between 1966 and 1969 and b52g longrange 
