<TEXT>
president bush and soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev signed a new trade pact friday that would lead to 
normalized economic relations between the two countries for the 
first time in nearly a half century 
but the bush administration emphasized that the provision most 
prized by gorbachev granting lower tariffs on soviet products sold 
in the united states will not go into effect until the soviet 
legislature passes a law providing free emigration 
at a white house signing ceremony bush said that he and 
gorbachev were looking forward to the passage of a soviet 
emigration law 
at a briefing afterward secretary of state james a baker iii 
said the agreement would not be sent to congress for ratification 
until the emigration law is passed 
the emigration law has gone through a first reading in the soviet 
legislature but has yet to be brought up for final passage 
the pact was signed without reference to gorbachevs handling of 
the independence movement in lithuania in recent weeks the 
administration had raised the possibility that it would refuse to 
sign a trade agreement unless gorbachev eased up on its economic 
blockade of the baltic republic 
deputy white house press secretary roman popadiuk told reporters 
that there has been no direct link between lithuania and trade 
however members of congress from both parties have insisted that 
there be just such a link 
said senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine the 
granting of mfn status in my mind is in mr gorbachevs hands he 
can achieve it with some rather modest changes in his policy toward 
the baltic states 
the united states will not give new trade benefits while the 
soviet noose continues to strangle lithuania said sen alfonse 
damato rny he talked to reporters before bush and gorbachev 
signed the agreement 
