<TEXT>
as unexpected as the stock markets latest 
upsurge to record highs may have been it certainly didnt seem to 
catch corporate insiders by surprise 
before the market began to take off five weeks ago top managers 
directors and major shareholders of corporations had been stepping 
up buying of their stocks for months to levels seldom seen over the 
past two decades 
by so doing they put some fresh luster on their reputation as a 
force to be reckoned with in the search for the right stock to buy 
at the right time 
since the waning months of 1989 according to tallies by various 
investment advisory services insiders have been consistently buying 
more shares of their companies stocks than they have sold in 
openmarket transactions 
to regular followers of the insiders activities that 
represented an even stronger endorsement of the market outlook than 
it might appear at first glance 
insiders often obtain stock through private means such as 
employee purchase plans and the exercise of options they receive as 
part of their pay 
thus in their openmarket activity analysts say they typically 
can be expected to be sellers about twothirds of the time and 
buyers in the remaining onethird or so of transactions 
because theyre often compensated with company stock about 
twice as many insiders normally sell than buy said stephen leeb 
in the newsletter personal finance 
but for the last few months buyers have actually outnumbered 
sellers every time this has happened in the past stocks across the 
board have rallied 
in calculating his insider indicator norman fosback editor 
of the advisory publication the insiders puts the normal buying 
line at 35 percent of the total transactions 
for a fiveweek period through midmay the indicator stood at a 
very bullish 60 percent 
the insiders are again telling the market that higher stock 
price levels are ahead fosback said the only way to describe 
their current activity is a buying panic 
the rationale for tracking the activities of insiders is 
straightforward enough fosback calls them americas most 
knowledgeable investors 
or as leeb observes what really drives stocks in the long run 
is whats happening on americas factory floors 
who are the best witnesses corporate insiders officers and 
directors who have firsthand knowledge of their firms strengths and 
weaknesses 
the closeup view does not always lead to unerring insight 
insiders had it right in 1980 and 1983 when they grew cautious just 
ahead of periods of flat or declining stock prices 
they gave no such warning however in 1987 leading up to the 
crash on black monday oct 19 of that year 
as if to make up for that omission they stampeded in with buy 
orders after the crash betting correctly that the market would 
rebound through the 2 years since then they have remained 
consistently if a little less spectacularly bullish 
when stocks tumbled early this year it appeared as though a bear 
market might have set in catching corporate insiders unaware but 
now says fosback the latest upside price burst has once again 
vindicated the insiders 
