<TEXT>
only now 45 years after world war ii ended in 
europe are many jewish survivors coming to grips with the trauma 
they suffered at the hands of nazi germany 
a recent survey found that 302404 of the nearly 1 million 
holocaust survivors who fled to israel from europe were still alive 
most are 65 to 80 an age at which experts say they will be taking 
stock of their lives 
the natural process of aging takes people back to deal with 
their pasts to make an account with their souls said ilana 
nahmias director of amcha which provides psychological counseling 
for survivors 
many seek a sympathetic ear for their nightmares paranoia 
loneliness 
scores have turned to amcha which has about 35 volunteer workers 
at its offices in jerusalem and ramat gan a suburb of tel aviv 
many of the volunteers are children of survivors 
amcha a nonprofit organization was the first recipient of 
reparations from east germany in the form of a 36 million grant 
in april its name means people or your people in hebrew 
and was a password holocaust survivors in europe used to identify 
each other 
its cases include 
a 60yearold man who spent the war years hiding from the nazis 
with the help of farmers and never shared his experiences with his 
family the home atmosphere became tense and his children had 
trouble fitting into the outside world 
a 72yearold survivor not given to dwelling on the past who 
began thinking constantly of his life in a concentration camp he 
was overwhelmed by a need to talk but did not want to burden his 
wife with his private terrors because she too had lived through 
the holocaust 
a man in his 70s who could not sleep because of a secret he 
could not tell his daughter that he had had a first wife and son 
who were killed by the nazis while he stood helpless 
counseling helped the first two and their families but the third 
man left the program after one session and refused the centers 
proposal to arrange for his daughter to join him in a meeting with 
counselors 
nahmias said there were several cases of survivors who had not 
told relatives and close friends about first families either 
because it was too painful or because they felt shame for not 
preventing the deaths 
we dont say we can cure pain she said we have no recipe 
but many feel they are going to explode that they have to tell 
about their experience now or it will be lost if they feel a little 
better its a lot 
some prefer talking to a tape recorder she said and the center 
has 200 hours of recorded testimonies 
the survivor can come and talk about what he wants said 
nahmias a former colonel in the army womens corps we dont try 
to find out if its true or matches historical events its enough 
if thats how he remembers something or how he wants to be 
remembered 
several cases involve survivors who were children during the 
holocaust about 50000 child victims live in israel to protect 
their privacy nahmias did not reveal the names of any of the 
survivors 
the amcha director related the case of a 55yearold woman who 
when her daughter left home to get married was suddenly faced again 
with the fear of separation she felt as a child while on the run 
from the nazis she had been passed from family to family 17 times 
nahmias said many child survivors were reluctant to speak of 
their experiences because they felt the suffering of those in the 
death camps was so much greater 
i didnt want to talk as a child i was ashamed of it said 
yossi peled who survived by hiding with a christian family in 
belgium and now is a major general in israels army 
eli and shoshana heyman a germanborn couple who survived work 
camps and auschwitz and now work as amcha volunteers said holocaust 
victims have difficulty speaking of it because nonsurvivors cannot 
relate to their experience 
sometimes you see it in their eyes they want to understand 
but they cant said shoshana heyman who is in charge of amchas 
archives its impossible when you want to explain it sounds so 
horrid that you cant explain 
she said they did not tell the terrible things even to their 
children but were able to talk with other survivors 
eli heyman a retired communal farmer who counsels lonely and 
troubled holocaust victims said he was haunted by the fact that 
survivors had such difficulty finding happiness 
what bothers me is that people who went through the holocaust 
in the end do not get by so well he said one has money but he 
does not get by he is not at one with himself he is divided you 
are not happy and that is the problem 
it is a not a remedy for a doctor to ask someone what hurts 
although he provides counseling heyman said i know it is not 
possible to find a solution 
