<TEXT>
an impasse between the united states and its 
european trading partners over cutting farm subsidies threatens to 
block a fouryear effort to liberalize the global trading system 
government officials said 
the warnings came at the end of a twoday meeting of trade and 
finance officials from two dozen industrialized nations 
officials had hoped the meeting would generate fresh momentum in 
the trade talks but instead they ended on a discordant note as the 
european community refused to accept us demands to sharply curtail 
its farm supports and export subsidies 
the trading blocs argument is simply not a tenable longterm 
position said gareth evans australias foreign affairs minister 
they will be putting at risk not just agriculture but the whole 
round of trade negotiations if they stick to a position as tight 
as that he said 
ministers of the organization for economic cooperation and 
development ended their talks thursday by saying they agreed to 
take urgent steps to reform agricultural policy as regards support 
and protection so as to permit greater liberalization of trade 
but in an unusual move their closing statement acknowledged 
differences on how an approach to these objectives should be 
expressed at this stage 
it was better to express these differences of views publicly 
than to try to paper them over said oecd secretarygeneral 
jeanclaude paye 
some 100 nations have been attempting to forge a new agreement to 
reduce trade barriers in 15 areas including agriculture textiles 
and services the talks began in uruguay in 1986 and are scheduled 
to end in december 
us trade representative carla hills had wanted this weeks oecd 
meeting to give a push to the trade talks but the talks appeared to 
do little more than show how far apart the two sides are 
at the heart of the fight is an american demand that the 
12nation ec do much more to rein in government spending on farm 
subsidies in particular by moving to eliminate costly export 
subsidies 
but ray macsharry the trading blocs top farm official said 
that is politically impossible and will not happen 
he contended that getting rid of the program would translate into 
higher farm prices in europe and cost the jobs of millions of 
farmers 
the subsidies allows expensive european farm products to compete 
with lower prices on the world market 
the united states complains the subsidies have enabled the 
community to increase its share of the world market and has 
responded by setting up its own export subsidy program 
american officials also pressed the community to open its markets 
wider to foreign farm products and reduce farm payments that 
encourage overproduction of crops 
the community rebuffed the pressure it called instead for an 
attempt to lower farm payments by first measuring a countrys trade 
performance in agriculture 
the ministers did promise to to make every effort to overcome 
the differences by a july 23 bargaining session in geneva by 
then the united states wants preliminary agreements or negotiating 
texts in all 15 areas under discussion 
the uruguay round of trade talks is being held under the auspices 
of the general agreement on tariffs and trade a forum and agreement 
for promoting freer trade 
oecd members are australia austria belgium britain canada 
denmark finland france greece iceland ireland italy japan 
luxembourg the netherlands new zealand norway portugal spain 
sweden switzerland turkey the united states and west germany 
