if an employee buyout can solve an airlines woes 
striking greyhound drivers think the same strategy could rescue the 
only nationwide bus company from the brink of bankruptcy 
a financial advisor hired by the drivers has asked to meet with 
greyhound lines inc to discuss a possible employee buyout 
the advisor brian freeman isnt new to the idea he is advising 
ual corp employees on their effort to complete a proposed 454 
billion buyout of the parent of united airlines 
in a letter dated may 29 to greyhound management and creditors 
freeman said he believed 100 percent employee ownership of all 
transportation operating and related assets together with a 
significant creditor restructuring is the best solution to the 
companys troubles 
freeman said thursday a price for a greyhound buyout had not been 
determined and no financing had been arranged although he said 
money should be available 
he said the union also is willing to discuss other alternatives 
within the shortterm i intend to make a specific proposal 
and begin to press aggressively toward a resolution freeman wrote 
on behalf of the amalgamated council of greyhound local unions 
