<TEXT>
an official of the international monetary fund 
is laying out stiff conditions for an effective shift from communism 
to a market economy in eastern europe 
thomas a wolf senior economist in the funds european 
department spoke thursday at a forum unrelated to the ussoviet 
summit meeting by coincidence he outlined his ideas just after 
president mikhail gorbachev at the soviet embassy a few blocks 
away made a plea to americans to let the soviets find their own way 
toward a system run on market principles 
the bush administration has opposed the soviet union joining the 
152 members of the imf and its sister organization the world bank 
present members include poland hungary and romania officials 
elsewhere in eastern europe including the soviet union have said 
they want to join too 
wolf listed five areas in which he said comprehensive reforms are 
needed in eastern europe he did not specify any country 
without action in each of these five areas a marketoriented 
reform will not be comprehensive and therefore is bound not to meet 
objectives of the reformers he said 
wolf said eastern european countries should 
eliminate much of the economic bureaucracy and let enterprises 
make their own decisions on matters such as prices wages 
employment investment output and foreign trade one way to do that 
is to make profit the main motivation for managers he said and 
another is to clearly define property rights 
initiate price reforms either by changing the governmentfixed 
prices to bring them close to the balance between supply and demand 
or by freeing prices entirely from government control or anything 
in between 
make wages depend on how much workers produce 
change the system of foreign trade including the buying and 
selling of foreign currencies 
create a new system of government influence on the economy 
since the state will no longer control enterprises directly it must 
influence them indirectly through taxes official spending and 
monetary policy as western governments now do 
its not enough to give enterprises greater autonomy or greater 
authority wolf said they need to be given incentives to use 
the authority that they are suddenly given 
but giving enterprises greater authority and greater incentive 
is still not enough he said 
they have to be given the responsibility to act through the 
market in order to raise or maximize profits and to raise wages in 
other words not to have the possibility of achieving those goals of 
higher profits and wages by negotiating special deals with the 
economic bureaucracy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

