imports of oil autos art and airplanes drove japans current 
account surplus down by the steepest amount in 10 years 
the surplus in the current account which measures trade in 
goods services and transfer payments fell 70 percent in april from 
a year earlier to 2 billion the surplus totaled 658 billion in 
april 1989 
it was the sharpest drop since the surplus contracted 95 percent 
in june 1979 
the current account is falling over the long term and 
eventually the surplus is going to shrink away said jan 
vandenberg an economist with merrill lynch in tokyo the vast 
majority of it is due to consumption demand in japan growing 
quite rapidly 
she said demand in japan is growing by about 4 percent a year 
compared to less than 2 percent a year in the united states 
aprils trade surplus which measures only trade in goods shrank 
50 percent to 402 billion the ministry said 
imports measured on the basis of settled contracts rose 17 
percent from yearago levels to 172 billion while exports fell 7 
percent to 212 billion the ministry said it was the seventh 
consecutive month exports have declined 
part of the decline was due to the weaker yen which reduced the 
value of japanese exports in dollar terms because of the time lag 
before lower prices result in higher export volume 
the dollar was trading at an average of 15720 yen in april 
compared to 13212 yen a year earlier a 16 percent devaluation 
finance ministry officials noted 
automobile exports in april fell 19 percent from a year earlier 
the sharpest drop in 20 years ministry officials said this was 
unusual because japanese automakers usually boost exports at the 
beginning of the new fiscal year in april after failing to fill 
export quotas for the previous year 
auto imports rose for the fifth month in a row up 72 percent in 
april last year 
steel exports dropped 23 percent in april the sixth month in a 
row that they have fallen about 20 percent from yearearlier levels 
the ministry said much of the decline was attributed to strong 
domestic demand for steel 
electric machinery exports fell 6 percent and semiconductor 
exports fell 85 percent 
meanwhile oil imports rose 22 percent along with heavy 
production by the organization of petroleum exporting countries and 
speculation that prices will rise in the future the ministry said 
aircraft imports rose 240 percent timber and wood imports rose 
42 percent and painting and art imports tripled 
invisible trade which includes transactions in insurance 
shipping tourism and other services posted a 184 billion deficit 
in april compared with a deficit of 129 billion a year earlier 
the ministry said the deficit was largely due to huge royalty 
payments by foreign affiliate firms in japan to their parent 
companies overseas 
large purchases of foreign securities by japanese investors 
produced a deficit of 53 billion in the longterm capital account 
down from a 164 billion deficit a year earlier 
an advisory council of the finance ministry said thursday that 
japans trade and current account surplus isnt a problem for the 
world economy and could help finance third world debtor nations and 
the us budget deficit 
finance minister ryutaro hashimoto also said friday that the 
surplus could help finance the development of eastern europe but he 
also said japan should consider ways to reduce the surplus 
particularly with respect to the united states 
the current account report does not include breakdowns of trade 
by country or region last month the finance ministry said japans 
monthly trade surplus with the united states fell from 454 billion 
a year earlier to 245 billion 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

