<DOCNO> AP900601-0224 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the recent plan to slowly shift the soviet union 
toward a market economy has cheered a group of us financiers who 
believe the reforms will bolster their efforts to bring a novel type 
of public finance to moscow 
the group signed an agreement with several soviet entities in 
april to finance three public projects with bonds designed to 
encourage the shift away from central planning and toward the market 
mechanism 
this project can help us find financial instruments that can 
help us solve several problems at the same time said sergei 
plekhanov deputy director of the institute of the usa and canada 
one of the soviet bodies involved in the agreement 
plekhanov said his country has massive social needs that go unmet 
because of its huge budget deficit at the same time households and 
state enterprises are sitting on tens of billions of rubles for want 
of goods to buy 
those problems were among the chief reasons behind the 
governments reform plan announced two weeks ago it laid out a 
fiveyear schedule of food price hikes banking reforms and partial 
privatizations designed to produce a socalled regulated market 
economy 
many radical soviet reformers found the plan too timid they 
criticized the government for backing away from the model created by 
poland which has attempted to move rapidly to a market economy by 
sharply devaluing the currency cutting state subsidies and freeing 
prices 
but jeffrey a sachs who initiated the financing project says 
the soviets gradual strategy is more humane than polishstyle 
shock therapy and more fitting for a country that hasnt known 
a market for 70 years sachs is unrelated to the harvard university 
professor of the same name who helped devise polands program 
rather than shrink the supply of money to match the amount of 
goods in the economy as poland is doing sachs wants to tap into 
the soviets big pool of savings to finance new projects 
using a nonprofit corporation called ecolink sachs group is 
working on plans to issue bonds in the soviet union to finance three 
projects an aids hospital an industrial project most likely a 
grainstorage facility and a prototype network of regional 
financial exchanges 
soviet citizens have a bad taste for bonds because the government 
forced purchases of bonds under stalin and later repudiated them 
also the ruble has little value because it cant be converted into 
western currencies and cant buy much at home 
ecolink argues that bonds can be made palateable however by 
having them pay interest in hard currency or in rubles that will 
guarantee the ability to buy scarce soviet resources the 
instruments could help contain inflation by absorbing excess cash 
and foster a move to allocating goods through the market rather than 
central planning agencies 
hard currency bonds would be appropriate for a grainstorage 
facility sachs suggests already the government spends large 
amounts of hard currency to import grain while perhaps 25 percent of 
soviet harvests rot for lack of storage bins and railroad grain 
cars he says therefore any investments that reduce grain losses 
should save hard currency 
thats an immediate economic benefit that can pay for itself 
says muriel siebert a financial market consultant and former new 
york state banking commissioner who is involved in ecolink 
in april the group asked us financial and legal experts to come 
forward with suggestions to turn the project ideas into reality 
sachs said dozens of investment banks and law firms have expressed 
interest 
the project backers are due to meet in moscow in july to draw up 
solid plans for the aids hospital and decide on the industrial 
project 
work on financial exchanges is just beginning siebert said 
ecolink is likely to propose that exchanges be set up to handle 
commodities that the soviets already have some experience in trading 
grain oil and gold 
talk of bond issues and soviet financial exchanges might have 
seemed farfetched just months ago plekhanov said now all these 
things are very much in line with the official policy i think that 
will speed things up 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

