<TEXT>
west germany joined france friday in banning british 
beef imports because of the mad cow disease that has killed 
thousands of cattle and prompted many britons to shun the meat 
however the european community offered a helping hand to 
britains cattle industry by offering to buy 20600 tons of meat 
british officials say the beef poses no threat to people who eat 
it that countrys meat and livestock commission accused the germans 
of responding to fears about a flood of cheap british beef rather 
than concern for public health 
britain made similar charges thursday about the french ban 
france which normally purchases more than half britains 
exported beef imposed its ban wednesday french officials said some 
meat might be tainted by the socalled mad cow disease or 
bovine spongiform encephalopathy 
the fatal nervous disorder causes a degeneration of brain tissue 
in infected cattle but british officials say there is no evidence 
the disease can be transmitted to humans 
west germany which already had barred imports of british beef 
still on the bone emulated france today by extending the ban to 
canned beef 
the agriculture ministry in bonn said it feared that british beef 
normally destined for france might be rerouted to west germany a 
total ban was necessary to protect consumers from infection the 
ministry said 
a team of french veterinarians sent to britain to assess the 
disease returned today to submit its report frances agriculture 
ministry said no decision on the duration of the ban would be made 
until after a meeting of the european communitys veterinary 
committee 
however british agriculture officials said the committee meeting 
had been postponed indefinitely 
european community officials denounced frances ban thursday as 
illegal and demanded it be revoked 
in brussels belgium ec headquarters announced today that the 
community would buy 20600 tons of british beef to help shore up 
falling meat prices 
the british meat and livestock commission said bans and fears 
arising from the disease are costing their industry about 850000 a 
day beef sales reportedly have fallen by about 30 percent in 
britain 
sir simon gourlay president of the national farmers union in 
britain called for retaliatory action f the bans persist but he 
did not elaborate 
the disease which was identified in britain in 1986 is blamed 
for killing 13648 cows there 
the cause is unknown because the symptoms are similar to 
scrapie a sheep disease it is assumed the disease was transmitted 
through cattle feeds they use sheep offal as a protein supplement 
