<DOCNO> AP900601-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
nintendo of america inc has sued a san 
francisco company to prevent distribution of a product that allows 
videogame players to change the way nintendo games are played 
the suit filed in us district court in san francisco claims a 
new product called game genie which is designed for play with a 
nintendo home video game system causes nintendo game characters to 
move at slower speeds or bypass obstacles originally programmed into 
the games it allows players to skip entire game levels and to add 
extra lives to a players life 
nintendo claims the product created by lewis galoob toys of 
south san francisco creates derivative works of copyrighted 
nintendo games 
us copyright law prevents third parties from creating and 
marketing derivatives of copyrighted video games without the 
express consent of the games owner howard lincoln nintendos 
senior vice president said in a press release announcing the suit 
thursday 
galoob introduced game genie on may 8 and sued nintendo on may 17 
after nintendo notified galoob of its claim of copyright 
infringement galoobs suit seeks a court declaration that game 
genie does not infringe nintendo copyrights 
nintendo filed its lawsuit after deciding to reject a proposal 
that nintendo give galoob a license to market game genie nintendo 
said 
lincoln compared game genie to speedup kits which were 
introduced for the popular arcade game pacman several years ago 
courts found such kits to be unauthorized derivative works of the 
original pacman game and enjoined their sale 
but steven m klein executive vice president and general counsel 
at galoob rejected any links to the pacman situation game genie is 
for use in private homes while the pacman speedup kits were 
designed for use in public video arcades he said in a telephone 
interview friday 
home owners can modify games selling them a product that 
allows them to do that is not illegal he said 
nintendo has conveniently ignored provisions of the copyright 
act that allows a product like this to be sold he said 
lincoln said game genie allows nintendo games to be mastered 
without any skill 
we cannot stand by while the essence of our business the 
creation of ever more challenging video games is put at risk by 
the game genie product he said 
klein did not dispute that game genie allows success with 
nintendo games without requiring skill but denied it would be 
detrimental to nintendo 
nintendo believes anything that interferes with their monopoly 
is a threat to their business he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900601-0243 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 1990 annual meetings and their scuffles and 
skirmishes are largely over and all the combatants are claiming 
victory even if the vote tallies dont show it 
the clearest winners this season were shareholders particularly 
the big institutional investors no longer content with passive 
ownership in the stocks of corporate america 
it was a banner year for institutional shareholders said 
gray davis the comptroller of california and a trustee of the 
states employee pension funds the largest in the nation 
davis was a prominent voice in pressing for a greater shareholder 
role in how companies are run during this annual meeting season the 
primary forum for dialogue between management and the owners they 
must answer to 
todd lang a new york attorney who specializes in corporate 
shareholder law said this has been the season when the 
institutions which own more than a majority of the equities in the 
united states have gone active with their positions 
shareholders placed more issues on annual meeting agendas this 
season and institutions became more vocal 
the shareholders biggest triumph came early in the season 
before and during the march 29 annual meeting of lockheed corp as 
dissident investor harold simmons waged a proxy fight with 
management to gain control of the defense contractors board of 
directors 
simmons lost but management was frightened he might win so the 
company granted big concessions including a promise to put at least 
one institutional investor representative on the board 
shareholders also won votes on several proposals among them a 
call for confidential proxy voting which would enable them to vote 
free from coercive pressure like in a political election 
in many companies shareholders sought a bigger voice in 
corporate policy and governance at the k mart corp and avon 
products inc meetings for example shareholders approved 
nonbinding resolutions asking management to submit the companies 
poison pill takeover defenses to shareholder votes 
these measures which make hostile takeovers more expensive 
generally fall under the jurisdiction of directors many 
shareholders dont like pills because they can block attractive 
prices stock in a takeover fight 
there was other evidence of shareholder activism although 
management proposals generally were approved in some cases they won 
by slimmer margins than in past votes 
at the time warner inc meeting managements stock incentive 
plan was approved but onequarter of the shares a relatively 
large bloc were cast against it 
management wasnt the only group coming up short this year 
stockholders also refused to rally around corporate takeover 
strategists 
at lockheed where simmons sought to install allies on the board 
and at american general corp where suitor torchmark inc had 
similar plans shareholders voted against the insurgents 
the outcome was expected to be the same at usx corp where 
shareholders voted on investor carl icahns nonbinding proposal to 
break up the steelenergy conglomerate the tally had not been 
completed by the end of last week but icahn had already said he 
expected to lose 
lang a partner with the firm weil gotshal amp manges in new york 
said the shareholders are listening to the dissidents ideas but 
theyre probably going to vote with their pocketbooks 
harry deangelo a finance professor at the university of 
michigan agreed theres a tendency for shareholders to go with 
the incumbent group unless the dissidents have a tangible proposal 
for distributing value or raising a companys stock price he said 
that was the case at lockheed and usx where simmons and icahn 
had ideas about ways to increase the price of the companies stock 
but did not offer shareholders any guarantees 
torchmark also had little concrete value to offer the suitor had 
encountered obstacles in its attempt to buy american general and 
resorted to a proxy fight 
dissidents had some victories however the belzberg family of 
canada managed to win one seat on the board of armstrong world 
industries inc though it subsequently scrapped a takeover offer 
for the company dissident shareholders upset the entire board of 
xtra corp a trailer leasing company 
icahn and simmons said they expected to eventually come out ahead 
financially even if they fell short of votes both said they expect 
management ultimately to respond to their complaints and take steps 
to boost the value of their stock 
shareholders did suffer disappointment this season perhaps the 
biggest came in their struggle with exxon corp over the oil 
companys environmental record 
the funds of which davis is a trustee and the pension funds of 
new york city and massachusetts had sought assurances from exxon 
that it would improve safety procedures following the exxon valdez 
oil spill off alaska last year management refused to adopt any 
environmental proposal made by shareholders 
nevertheless davis said were not going away and exxon will 
have to come to terms with its environmental indifference 
davis said he expects shareholder power particularly that of 
the big institutions to increase over the next 10 years as the 
pension funds increase their stakes in us companies he predicted 
management will be forced to consult regularly with shareholders 
right now he acknowledged shareholders have more leverage in 
situations where management faces a threat such as a takeover or 
proxy fight but he looks for that to change 
lang agreed that institutional shareholders have enormous 
potential power but said their new activism poses a number of 
legal questions 
for example under securities and exchange commission 
regulations institutional investors are subject to different 
disclosure requirements according to their level of activism but if 
an institution that was previously considered passive becomes more 
activist it could find itself in violation of sec rules lang said 
shareholders face other dilemmas as they seek a bigger role 
especially as they clamor for places on boards of directors 
a member of a board is supposed to represent all the 
shareholders said john lubin a management professor at the 
wharton school of the university of pennsylvania if they go on 
the board legally and in every sense theyre not supposed to 
represent their own interests 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

