<TEXT>
a survey of purchasing managers indicated on 
friday an improvement in manufacturing in may but economists said 
the report was overshadowed and contradicted by government 
unemployment numbers 
gains in production and new orders led the increase the second 
in as many months for the purchasing managers index 
the rise in the index is more a sign that the manufacturing slump 
has hit bottom than a precursor of a strong recovery said james 
solloway director of economic research at argus research inc in 
new york 
it does show some stability in manufacturing coming in but 
things are still soft solloway said 
economists also said the report by the national association of 
purchasing management was probably influenced by increased 
automobile production that is not being matched by sales 
the purchasing managers index rose to 507 percent in may up 
from 502 percent the month before a reading above 50 indicates the 
manufacturing economy is generally expanding below 50 that it is 
generally declining 
it was the highest level for the purchasing managers index since 
it reached 527 percent in april 1989 
the index is giving us a rosier picture of manufacturing than 
is justified allen sinai an economist at boston co in new york 
said noting weak unemployment figures 
the government said friday the unemployment rate fell 01 
percentage point to 53 percent in may however an increase of 
164000 new jobs was almost entirely due to the addition of 
temporary census workers private economists had expected 
nongovernment industries to create at least 125000 new jobs in 
may far greater than the 19000 that were added 
