<TEXT>
international business machines corp said friday 
it has signed its biggest contract yet with the soviet union under 
which it will supply over 13000 personal computers for use in 
schools 
it is a significant step up from the level of soviet business 
weve been doing before said ibm spokesman mac jeffery 
the value of the contract was not disclosed but jeffrey said the 
soviets will pay in a convertible currency and that they received a 
discount comparable to the one ibm offers other customers for 
computers bought for educational use 
barry bosak an industry analyst at smith barney harris upham amp 
co said the contract could be worth 20 million to 30 million 
depending on the discount and the types of printers and other 
equipment included he said it probably ranks among the largest 
sales of computer equipment to the soviet union by a western company 
jeffery said ibm has been selling computers in the soviet union 
since 1975 but he declined to quantify the earlier saleswe hope 
this will lead to other things he said 
ibm and the ussr state committees for education and 
informatics said in a statement that the contract could form the 
basis for the buildup of assembly operations for personal computers 
in the ussr and that feasibility studies on such assembly 
operations have been launched 
it is something that both sides are seriously looking at 
jeffery said declining to elaborate 
bosak said the possibility of building soviet assembly plants is 
more important than the size of the contract setting up an assembly 
operation would give them ibm a working base he said 
as part of the deal with the state education committee ibm will 
provide 150 educational software packages that have been translated 
into russian in addition ibm will work with outside software 
companies to provide additional applications programs and will train 
soviet software engineers to write educational software jeffery 
said 
ibm also will train teachers to use the computers he said 
the contract is for ibms personal system2 machines featuring 
intel corps 80286 microprocessor the most sophisticated 
microprocessor allowed to be exported to the soviet union by us 
companies under current export rules jeffery said 
shipments will begin in september in time for some schools to 
begin using the machines in the 199091 school year ibm said 
