<DOCNO> AP900601-0252 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
argentina is to resume 
negotiations next week with creditor banks over the possible 
resumption of interest payments for the first time in two years on 
its 60 billion foreign debt local newspapers reported friday 
however talks are likely to be contentious with creditor banks 
apparently seeking more than the argentine government is offering to 
pay the reports stated 
citing sources in the economy ministry the daily clarin reported 
the government is prepared to pay 70 million a month for three 
months but creditor banks want a minimum 100 million monthly for 
the rest of 1990 
the daily la nacion reported foreign bankers dont want monthly 
payments at all but rather a lump sum before negotiations resume 
the 11monthold government of president carlos menem is seeking 
debt forgiveness approval for debt capitalization and new loans 
its mission to new york will be led by the presidentdesignate of 
the central bank javier gonzalez fraga 
fraga told the financial daily el cronista comercial that foreign 
banks basically want interest payments they have received 
virtually nothing in more than two years 
negotiations with a steering committee that represents banks owed 
about 40 billion mostly us banks are likely to be difficult 
the us government in january ordered banks to more than double 
their reserves set aside to cover potentially bad loan to argentina 
cutting into bank earnings 
overdue interest may total 85 billion this year the argentine 
government conceded in a letter to the international monetary fund 
last friday 
