defunct benefit brand cereal the company said thursday 
minnesota attorney general hubert humphrey iii and the attorneys 
general in iowa and wisconsin alleged that an advertisement claiming 
that benefit removes cholesterol from your body were false and 
misleading 
golden valleybased general mills said thursday it agreed to pay 
each of the three states 7000 the settlement is not an admission 
of wrongdoing the company said 
the settlement was the fastest and least costly way to resolve 
differences over a single newspaper ad for a product that hasnt 
been sold for over five months the company said in a statement 
general mills said it took exception with humphreys description 
of the settlement he said that under the agreement general mills 
will not make any similar claims that its products remove 
cholesterol from the body 
although the golden valley based company removed benefit cereal 
from store shelves last winter humphrey said nothing prevented the 
company from resurrecting a similar product with the same highly 
questionable claims 
these cholesterol claims have gotten out of control said 
humphrey to imply that a single product will magically remove 
cholesterol is misleading and deceptive to consumers it takes an 
overall lowfat lowcholesterol diet to help reduce cholesterol 
we strongly disagree with his characterization of the 
settlement general mills said 
company spokeswoman kathy newton said the settlement applies only 
to a single newspaper ad printed in august of last year 
she said the interim ad featured a pacman cartoon character 
gobbling up the word cholesterol in the phrase benefit removes 
cholesterol from your body 
humphrey has urged the federal food and drug administration to 
ban health claims unless there is scientific consensus that the 
claims are true he also urged the federal agency to spell out the 
exact wording that food manufacturers must use in making any health 
claims about their products 
