<TEXT>
nbc joining in the abc and cbs challenge of the 
nielsen peoplemeter ratings system said friday it is 
seriously concerned about the systems value to the industry 
the ac nielsen co promptly fired back saying in a statement 
it had investigated the systems reports of decreasing levels of 
network viewing and we feel its a real decline 
the peoplemeters the industry ratings standard since the fall 
of 1987 are vieweractivated devices that record what shows are 
being watched and which members of a participating family are 
watching 
the networks contend that the peoplemeter figures undercount 
the real audience and that the system which is in 4000 homes is 
flawed 
abc on thursday fired the first round against the system saying 
it would use its own formula of ratings analysis to determine if it 
should give makegoods to advertisers of abc shows that get 
ratings lower than abc had promised 
makegoods are commercial slots given free to businesses when 
their ads air on shows with lessthanexpected ratings ads are sold 
on the basis of the networks prediction of the size and makeup of 
the audience 
nbc in a statement friday said it was troubled by what it 
called the unexplained aberrations in the nielsen people meter 
ratings and said it was taking a close look at abcs plan and 
other possibilities 
however it also said such steps are only interim solutions to 
the problem and called for networks and advertisers alike to work 
for a viable system that would eliminate concerns about accuracy 
and reliability 
cbs research vice president david poltrack who has been a strong 
critic of the peoplemeter methodology said in an interview that 
the network has not yet reviewed all the options it may have in 
the dispute 
it probably will start the review monday he said and start 
looking at the advertising industry reactions to abcs plan 
he also said he felt that the peoplemeter systems deficiences 
and instability make it an unreliable tool for television audience 
measurement 
we feel the peoplemeter system is not responsible for the 
viewing decline and its the buyers of advertising time who 
ultimately will decide the validity of each networks proposal 
said nielsen spokeswoman jo laverde 
several advertising agency executives panned the abc plan and 
came to the defense of the nielsen rarings system 
steve sternberg manager of broadcast research at the ad agency 
bozell inc said his agency feels the decline in tv audiences 
evident in the nielsen ratings are genuine rather than due to faults 
in the measurement system 
the abc plan to base audience guarantees on a threeyear average 
rather than the upcoming seasons actual results is a blatant 
attempt to lock advertisers into historical viewing levels 
favorable to abc in the face of deteriorating network viewing 
kevin burns and john hunt of the ad agency ogilvy amp mather wrote in 
a commentary on the abc plan 
they said the audience guarantees were enacted to protect 
advertisers in return for making a sizeable longterm commitment 
in effect the abc proposal would provide a gurantee for the 
network rather than the advertiser despite the current turmoil in 
the medium we dont believe it is the advertisers responsibility 
to guarantee the networks a profit they wrote 
richard kostyra media services director at the j walter 
thompson ad agency said the abc plan could move a lot of money 
into fox which has said it would give the normal guarantees on 
sales on its network 
he said it would also encourage advertisers to spend more to 
advertise on cable television syndicated shows and alternative 
media outlets such as those aimed at reaching women in doctors 
offices or beauty parlors and shoppers in the supermarket checkout 
lines 
paul schulman who heads an ad buying service that carries his 
name said the guarantees are only one of the items to be negotiated 
on buying ad time 
this isnt the key to the whole negotiations we have to see 
what kind of price increasaes they are seeking he said 
